        <p>
            Ascending order means from the smallest to the largest.
        </p>
        <p>
            To arrange fractions in ascending order, first convert them into their equivalent fractions using the same denominator.
        </p>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Arrange the following fractions in ascending order.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>\frac{1}{3},\frac{2}{5},\frac{3}{4},\frac{1}{2}</me>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                We first find the LCM of denominators of the fractions in the given sequence. <m>{\color{blue}3,5,4} \text{ and } {\color{blue}2}.</m>
                            </p>
                            <tabular right="medium">
                                <row bottom="medium">
                                    <cell><m>{\color{red}2}</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>{\color{blue}3}</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>{\color{blue}5}</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>{\color{blue}4}</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>{\color{blue}2}</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row bottom="medium">
                                    <cell><m>{\color{red}2}</m></cell>
                                    <cell>3</cell>
                                    <cell>5</cell>
                                    <cell>2</cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row bottom="medium">
                                    <cell><m>{\color{red}3}</m></cell>
                                    <cell>3</cell>
                                    <cell>5</cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row bottom="medium">
                                    <cell><m>{\color{red}5}</m></cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                    <cell>5</cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell></cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                    <cell>1</cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>
                            <p>
                                <m> {\color{red}2} \times {\color{red}2} \times  {\color{red}3} \times  {\color{red}5} = 60</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The LCM of <m>{\color{blue}3,5,4} \text{ and } {\color{blue}2} \text{ is } 60.</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Now, rewrite the fractions to have a common denominator.
                            </p>
                            <sidebyside>
                                    <p>
                                       <md>
                                        <mrow>\frac{1}{3} \amp = \frac{1 \times {\color{red}20}}{3 \times {\color{red}20}} </mrow>
                                        <mrow></mrow>
                                        <mrow> \amp = \frac{20}{60} </mrow>
                                       </md> 
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        <md>
                                            <mrow>\frac{2}{5} \amp = \frac{2 \times {\color{blue}12}}{5 \times {\color{blue}12}} </mrow>
                                            <mrow></mrow>
                                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{24}{60} </mrow>
                                        </md>
                                    </p>
                            </sidebyside>
                            <sidebyside>
                                   <p>
                                        <md>
                                            <mrow>\frac{3}{4} \amp = \frac{3 \times {\color{green}15}}{ 4 \times {\color{green}15}} </mrow>
                                            <mrow></mrow>
                                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{45}{60} </mrow>
                                        </md>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        <md>
                                            <mrow>\frac{1}{2} \amp = \frac{1 \times {\color{yellow}30}}{2 \times {\color{yellow}30}} </mrow>
                                            <mrow></mrow>
                                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{30}{60} </mrow>
                                        </md>
                                    </p>
                            </sidebyside>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Arrange the fractions in ascending order based on their numerator, since we have a common denominator of <m>60</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{20}{60},\frac{24}{60},\frac{30}{60},\frac{45}{60}</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Now, write the corresponding fractions in their original form as per the arranged order above.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{1}{3},\frac{2}{5},\frac{1}{2},\frac{3}{4}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Arrange the following fractions in ascending order.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        \frac{1}{4}, \frac{3}{5}, \frac{1}{2}, \frac{7}{10}
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Convert each fraction into a percentage.
                            </p>
                            <sidebyside>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{1}{4} \times 100\% = 25\%</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{3}{5} \times 100\% = 60\%</m>
                                </p>
                            </sidebyside>
                            <sidebyside>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{1}{2} \times 100\% = 50\%</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\frac{7}{10} \times 100\% = 70\%</m>
                                </p>
                            </sidebyside>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Arrange the percentages in ascending order.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>25\%, 50\%, 60\%, 70\%</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Finally, write the corresponding fractions in the order of the arranged  percentages above.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The correct order is <m>\frac{1}{4},\frac{1}{2},\frac{3}{5},\frac{7}{10}.</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
